@article{Svartman2005,
abstract = {Polyploidy, the presence of more than two chromosome sets, is common in plants, but extremely rare in animals. The absence of polyploid organisms with well-differentiated sex chromosomes suggests that the disruption of the dosage between autosomes and sex chromosomes is incompatible with normal development. Thus, the announcement in 1999 of tetraploidy in a mammal, the South American red vizcacha rat Tympanoctomys barrerae, provoked great interest, even though the definitive proof of tetraploidy, the presence of four copies of each chromosome, was never provided. Here we used classical and molecular cytogenetics to test the ploidy level of T. barrerae and demonstrate that only two copies of each chromosome are present in this karyotype. The red vizcacha rat is clearly diploid and the amplification and dispersion of repetitive sequences best explain the large genome size of this mammal. Thus, polyploidy in mammals remains as unlikely as it has always been. Published by Elsevier Inc. The South American red vizcacha rat, Tympanoctomys barrerae, has the highest chromosome number (2n = 102) [1] and the largest genome size yet described among mammals [2]. It is a member of the family Octodontidae, a taxon that comprises 12 species of endemic, monophyletic South American rodents [3-8]. Octodontidae diploid numbers range from 2n = 38 to 2n = 102, with a median of 54-58 chromosomes. Common features of Octodontidae karyotypes include the presence of mostly bi-armed chromosomes, pericentro-meric constitutive heterochromatin, and a marker autosome pair with a nucleolus organizer region (NOR). Karyotypic studies in Octodontidae have been restricted to conventionally stained and C-banded karyotypes [2,8,9], methods that provide only limited karyotypic information. Molecular cytogenetic and longitudinal banding methods, which provide much more detail, have never been reported for any Octodontidae. We used several cytogenetic approaches to test the ploidy level of T. barrerae (2n = 102) and to dissect the composition of its extremely large genome. We performed fluorescence in situ hybridization (FISH) with individual chromosome probes (chromosome painting) of Octodon degus, a related species with 2n = 58, the proposed ancestral diploid number for all Octodontidae [8]. We used total genomic DNA of both rodent species as probes for FISH to assess the degree of homology between their genomes, and we hybridized a limited number of human chromosome paints to T. barrerae cells. The molecular cytogenetic analysis of T. barrerae chromosomes was complemented with G banding. Results and discussion DNA from flow-sorted chromosomes of O. degus was used as probes for FISH. The chromosome content of the 25 sorted peaks was established by hybridizing back to O. degus metaphases (Fig. 1). Not all peaks contained single chromosomes, but good paints were obtained for 19 chromosomes. Some chromosomes were found in two peaks (i.e., pairs 1 and 5), showing a notable hetero-morphism in DNA content of some homologue pairs of O.},
